FR0.Description: A clean, foul-free surface; red and/or black AF paint or bare metal surface.

FR10.Description: Light shades of red and green (incipient slime). Bare metal and painted surfaces are visible beneath the fouling.

FR20.Description: Slime as dark green patches with yellow or brown coloured areas (advanced slime). Bare metal and painted surfaces may be obscured by the fouling.

FR30.Description: Grass filaments up to 3 inches (76 mm) in length, projections up to 1⁄4 inch (6.4 mm) in height; or flat network of filaments, green, yellow, or brown in color, or soft non calcareous fouling such as sea cucumbers, sea grapes, or sea squirts projecting up to 1⁄4 inch (6.4 mm) in height. The fouling cannot be easily wiped off by hand.

FR40.Description: Calcareous fouling in the form of tube worms less than 1⁄4 inch (6.4 mm) in diameter or height.

FR50.Description: Calcareous fouling in the form of barnacles, less than 1⁄4 inch (6.4 mm) in diameter or height.

FR60.Description: Combination of tubeworms and barnacles less than 1⁄4 inch (6.4mm) in diameter or height.

FR70.Description: Combination of tubeworms and barnacles greater than 1⁄4 inch (6.4 mm) in diameter or height.

FR80.Description: Tubeworms closely packed together and growing upright away from surface. Barnacles growing one on top of another, 1⁄4 inch (6.4 mm) or less in height. Calcareous shells appear clean or white in color.

FR90.Description: Dense growth of tubeworms with barnacles, 1⁄4 inch (6.4 mm) or greater in height. Calcareous shells brown in color (oysters and mussels); or with slime or grass overlay.

FR100.Description: All forms of fouling present, soft and hard, particularly soft sedentary animals without calcareous covering (tunicates) growing over various forms of hard growth.

PDR20.Description: AF paint missing from edges, corners, seams, welds rivet or bolt heads to expose anti corrosion (AC) paint. (undercoat)

PDR30.Description: AF paint missing from slightly curved or flat areas to expose underlying AC paint; An AF paint with visible brush swirl marks within the outermost layer – not extending into underlying layers of paint.

PDR40.Description: AF paint missing from intact blisters to expose AC paint or an AF coating with visible brush swirl marks exposing the next underlying layer of AF or AC paint.

PDR50.Description: AF blisters ruptured to expose intact AC paint.

PDR60.Description: AF/AC paint missing or peeling to expose steel substrate with corrosion present.

PDR70.Description: AF/AC paint removed from edges, corners, seams, welds rivet or bolt heads to expose steel substrate with corrosion present.

PDR80.Description: Ruptured AF/AC blisters on slightly curved or flat surfaces with corrosion or corrosion stains present.

PDR90.Description: Area corrosion of steel substrate with no AF/AC paint cover due to peeling or abrasion damage.

PDR100.Description: Area corrosion showing visible surface evidence of pitting, scaling, and roughening of steel substrate.

report.overview:
Franmarine Underwater Services (FUS) were engaged by Austal to carry-out an In-water hull clean (IWHC), Propeller Polish and Bow Thruster Clean on Hull 811. 

  • All in-water maintenance work was conducted by qualified divers trained in under water inspection and cleaning techniques and in accordance with client requirements and time schedules. 
  • The hull clean was carried out using a combination of soft rubber squeegees and hard plastic scrapers.  
  • The propellers were hydraulically cleaned to Ruberts Scale A/B+ on all surfaces of each blade.  
  •  The bowthruster propeller was cleaned with the use of a 6000psi water blaster due to lack of direct access to the propeller through the tunnel grates.  
  •  All work was then documented using HD stills photography. 

Diving operations were conducted from the Austal land backed wharf using a 4 person dive team in accordance with AS/NZS 2299.1:2015.  

Documents used to assist the project: 

  • AS/NZS
    2299.1:2015 
  • FRANMARINE
    Operations Manual 
  • Client information on the day.
report.findings:
· All underwater hull surfaces and appendages were cleaned to remove all marine fouling without causing any damage to the coating system. A combination of soft rubber squeegees and harder scrapers (for propeller shafts) were used. 

· Prior to the clean biofouling was reported as predominately soft growth in the form of weed/slime and sponge consistent with FR-20. Hard marine growth in the form of tube worm and
juvenile barnacles (FR-50) were attached to the niche areas and areas of antifoul coating (AFC) defect. The total coverage of hull plate fouling was approximately 50-60%. 

· On completion of the clean the divers confirmed that all underwater hull plate surfaces and appendages were free of marine fouling consistent with FR-0.

sternArrangement2.comments:
• Port and starboard trim tabs were found to have an FR of 20-40 pre clean
  • Wire wool was used to clean metal surfaces on both trim tabs

propeller.comments:
· Port and starboard side propellers were found to be a five (5) blade fixed pitch type propeller with a FR of 80 pre clean.

· Hydraulically polishing the propellers achieved a Ruberts Scale A/B+ grade surface finish. It should be noted that there was difficulty accessing the propeller roots with the hydraulic tooling. 

· Post clean inspection of the propellers revealed no significant signs of damage or visual anomalies. All leading/trailing edges and propeller tips were reported as smooth to touch and in good condition. 

  • Port and Starboard propeller shafts were found to have an FR of 60 pre clean
  • Steel scrapers and wire wool was used to clean propeller shafts and a FR of 0 was acheived.

  • Port and Starboard rudders were found to have a PDR of 10 to 50, with areas of delamaination occouring along weld semes and edges.

bilgeKeels.comments:
• Port and starboard bilge keels were found to have an FR of 20 - 30 pre clean.
  • Port and starboard bilge keels were cleaned to remove all marine fouling without causing any damage to the coating system. A combination of soft rubber squeegees and harder scrapers were used.

stabiliserFins.comments:
• Port and starboard stabiliser fins were found to have an FR of 20 - 30 pre clean.
  • Port and starboard stabiliser fins were cleaned to remove all marine fouling without causing any damage to the coating system. A combination of soft rubber squeegees and harder scrapers were used.

hullAnodes.comments:
• All hull anodes were found to have an FR of 30-60 pre clean.
  • A stiff scraper was used to clean all anodes.

thrustersGratingsTunnelAssembly.comments:
• The bow thruster propeller was found to be badly fouled with hard marine fouling in the form of tube worm and marine barnacle. This was consistent with FR-100 at 100% coverage.  
  • The bow thruster propeller was cleaned with the use of a 6000psi water blaster due to lack of direct access to the propeller through the tunnelgrates.  
  • Extreme caution was used during the water blasting process to ensure that contact with any coated surface of the bow thruster tunnel was not made.  
  • On completion of the clean the divers confirmed that all propeller surfaces were free of marine fouling (FR-0).
